# Battery

The batteries we see in real life are [[61-Archive/20220413102600-real-battery|real batteries]], but they are not [[61-Archive/20220413103516-ideal-battery|ideal]].

## Characteristics

Battery [[61-Archive/20220318120826-voltage|voltage]] is not constant, so it has to be **stabalized** to provide _predictable performance_

![../60-Meta-Attachments/fa161c82d8f6a0140348e61d5c310827.png](data:image/png;base64,)

To solve this, most battery-operated systems need a [[61-Archive/20220221170530-regulator|regulator]] to provide a **constant [[61-Archive/20220318120826-voltage|voltage]]**.

## Types

Two big categories:

1. Primary Battery
2. Rechargeable

| Primary Battery           | Voltage | Energy ($MJ/kg$) | Remarks                                                                   |
| ------------------------- | ------- | ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Zinc chloride/carbon      | 1.5V    | 0.13             | Inexpensive                                                               |
| Akaline                   | 1.5V    | 0.4-0.59         | Most commonly used                                                        |
| Silver oxide              | 1.55V   | 0.47             | Very expensive, only used in button cells                                 |
| Lithium manganese dioxide | 3.0V    | 0.83-1.01        | Expensive and slow discharge. For high drain usage only                   |
| Mercury oxide             | 1.35V   | 0.5              | Constant voltage, but banned in most countries because of health concerns |

| Rechargeable | Voltage | Energy ($MJ/kg$) | Remarks                                                                  |
| ------------ | ------- | ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| NiCd         | 1.2V    | 0.14             | Inexpensive, but with "memory" effect                                    |
| Lead-acid    | 2.1V    | 0.14             | High discharge rate and environmental [[62-Encyclopedic/20220504155837-hazard|hazard]] |
| NiMH         | 2.1V    | 0.36             | Heavy and high discharge rate                                            |
| NiZn         | 1.6V    | 0.36             | Newly introduced in 2009 and limited size only                           |
| Lithium ion  | 3.6V    | 0.46             | Low discharge and volatile (explode if short circuit)                    |
